  { question: "What is BAC and how is it measured?", answer: "BAC (Blood Alcohol Concentration) is the percentage of alcohol in your bloodstream by volume. A BAC of 0.08% means there are 0.08 grams of alcohol per 100 milliliters of blood. BAC can be measured with a breathalyzer, blood test, or estimated using the Widmark formula based on drinks consumed, body weight, gender, and time." },
  { question: "What is the legal BAC limit for driving?", answer: "In most US states and many countries, the legal BAC limit for driving is 0.08%. However, impairment begins well below this level. Some jurisdictions have lower limits — for example, 0.05% in Utah and many European countries. For commercial drivers, the limit is typically 0.04%, and for drivers under 21, most states enforce zero tolerance (0.00-0.02%)." },
  { question: "How long does it take for BAC to reach zero?", answer: "The body metabolizes alcohol at an average rate of about 0.015% BAC per hour, regardless of body weight, gender, or how much you drank. This means it takes roughly one hour to eliminate one standard drink from your system. A BAC of 0.08% takes about 5.3 hours to return to zero. Only time reduces BAC — coffee, cold showers, and food do not speed up alcohol metabolism." },
  { question: "Why does gender affect BAC?", answer: "Gender affects BAC because of differences in body water content. Men typically have about 68% body water, while women average about 55%. Since alcohol distributes through body water, women generally reach higher BAC levels than men of the same weight after consuming the same amount of alcohol. This difference is captured by the Widmark factor used in BAC calculations." },
  { question: "What counts as one standard drink?", answer: "In the United States, one standard drink contains 14 grams of pure alcohol. This is equivalent to 12 ounces (355 mL) of regular beer at 5% ABV, 5 ounces (148 mL) of wine at 12% ABV, or 1.5 ounces (44 mL) of distilled spirits at 40% ABV (80 proof). Many cocktails and craft beers contain more than one standard drink per serving." }
